    "# Example Inserts\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Sectioning and Structure\n",
    "\n",
    "There is some variation between modules and documentation bassed on structure and needs of the model. However there are some materials, or ingredients if you will, that will remain consistent between modules. These include: Module Header, module introduction, sections representing components of module, section introductions, methodologies, relevant inputs, and relevant outputs.\n",
    "\n",
    "These should be referred to in a consistent manner throughout the document to inform tables of contents, indices, and auditing materials. \n",
    "\n",
    "```markdown\n",
    "# Module Name\n",
    "section title and only appears once\n",
    "\n",
    "## Module Introduciton\n",
    "- subsection header\n",
    "\n",
    "## Section Title \n",
    "- subsection header that introduces distinct portions of each module that \n",
    "require separate methodological descriptions and equations\n",
    "\n",
    "### Section Introduction \n",
    "- subsubsection header to introduce the concept\n",
    "\n",
    "### Methodology \n",
    "- subsubsection header used to start descriptions\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Relevant Inputs or Relevant Outputs\n",
    "emphasized headers should be used to report the inputs and outputs of the \n",
    "relevant subsection. These usually include tables and bulleted lists. Tables \n",
    "of inputs should include: \n",
    "\n",
    "- Variable\n",
    "- Definition\n",
    "- Default\n",
    "- Min\n",
    "- Max\n",
    "\n",
    "If there is no application for one of these (default, min, or max particularly), \n",
    "do not leave the table cell blank. Please include \"--\" or \"NA\" depending on \n",
    "what makes the most sense. \n",
    "\n",
    "*Alternate Headers* alternate headers may be used at the discretion of the author.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "There may be expanded uses for subsubsection headers and emphasized headers. The ones outlined above are only the expected uses. Feel free to use more at the discretion of the author. \n",
    "\n",
    "## Images, Figures, and Tables\n",
    "\n",
    "### Linking - Internal and External\n",
    "\n",
    "This is an important feature of the scientific documentation. A document this large can be difficult to navigate, so anything that improves the users ability to find what they need efficiently should be optimized. \n",
    "\n",
    "```markdown\n",
    "\n",
    "There are 3 main structures to \"label\" parts of the document: \n",
    "- #sec (sections)\n",
    "- #tbl (tables)\n",
    "- #fig (figures)\n",
    "\n",
    "Naming is important for tracking and should appear with hyphens, not spaces. \n",
    "There is no formal process to inform how you name, but it is recommended that \n",
    "it is descriptive of the item you are labeling and it is concise to make \n",
    "referencing easier.\n",
    "\n",
    "When you label anything, you must start with the structure type (sec, tbl, fig). Next you must indicate the 3 letter module abbreviate: \n",
    "- an = Animal\n",
    "- ma = Manure\n",
    "- sc = Soil and Crop\n",
    "- fe = Feed Storage\n",
    "- ec = Economics\n",
    "- cx = Connecting or Gray Documents\n",
    "\n",
    "When uploading new images, screenshots, flowcharts or other image resources, the 3 letter abbreviations should be the LEADING part of the file name. The rest of the file name should be descriptive of the content of the image separated by underscores (_). If the image is used for a title page or representative of the larger model, the leading file name should be \"rufas.\"\"\n",
    "\n",
    "**Note** \n",
    "Files that include flow charts should indicate such in the file. For example, a flow chart of the decision tree in the animal module should be names \"ani_flow_decision_tree\". Similarly, if the image is a screenshot of a section of code from the module, the file name should include 'code'. For example, a code screenshot for the manure module should be named \"man_code_description\" or something similar.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Linking internally and externally is the first step, however it can be hard to keep track of labels and how they have been used and referenced. That is the main reason we have the auditing tool. If you are creating new labels or new reference links, **be sure to check the auditor to make sure that there is no repeat labels or incorrect references**\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### Example of a Figure \n",
    "\n",
    "All figures and images must be uploaded in the \"references.\" When you upload your fig/img, you may name the file (best to keep it short and sweet)...\n",
    "\n",
    "<!-- #fig-animal-icon is how the code adds figures to TOC, like a label -->\n",
    "\n",
    "```markdown\n",
    "\n",
    "![Animal module icon](../resources/images/ani_icon.png.png){#fig-animal-icon width=35%}\n",
    "\n",
    "-->[Caption for the image or figure]\n",
    "--> #fig-animal-icon = #indicates the type of file-label-for-auditing\n",
    "--> width=35% = sizing adjusted as needed\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "The output is below : \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "![Animal module icon](../resources/images/ani_icon.png){#fig-animal-icon width=35%}\n",
    "\n",
    "### Example of a Table\n",
    "\n",
    "Our documentation include quite a few tables with long, detailed definitions and extended variable names. It is important that these are all legible and consistently formated for readability. This requires precise alignment of gridlines-- which can get tedious. Additionally, any updates to variables or defaults may make this process more time consuming in the future. \n",
    "\n",
    "Instead, we have four excel files that correspond to each existing module. In each file, sheets are named by their label id (see next section for more on id logic). That way, you can auto-generate a .txt file with your table properly sized and formated using the make_grid_table.py (quarto-scidoc>scripts). The .txt file output will show up in quarto-scidoc>output>tables.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Option 1 - Generate Directly from a .csv File\n",
    "This is the preferred method to generate a table because it is the most straightforward and requires the least amount of formatting. You can use the make_markdown_table function in the make_grid_table.py script to generate a markdown table from a .csv file. The .csv file should be formatted with the appropriate columns (Variable, Definition, Default, Min, Max) and should be saved in the resources/table_data folder. The name of your file should match the label used in the documentation. This will help with traceback and auditing. \n",
    "\n",
    "All tables begin with the \"tbl-\" prefix followed with the 3 letter acronym for the module where the table belongs (e.g. \"ani\" for animal). The final segments (also separated by hyphens) should be short but descriptive. For example, the table of abbreviations is labeled \"tbl-abbrevs\" (it is outside of any module so no module abbreviation is used) and the corresponding .csv file is named \"tbl-abbrev.csv\".\n",
    "\n",
    "The main adjustments you will need to make are the label, tbl-cap (caption), and the file name in the make_markdown_table function. The rest of the code can be copied and pasted as is.\n",
    "\n",
    "If you are having trouble running this, be sure to check the sys.path.append location and the actual .csv file location."
   ]
