    "### Option 2 - Create a .csv File before Generating the Table from your File\n",
    "A comprehensive, step-by-step guide to this process is available in qmd > scripts > quarto_python_test > python_tables_example files created by Clay. They also add some description details to option 1, so it may be good to review regardless of your preferred option.\n",
    "\n",
    "## Equation Templates and ID Logic\n",
    "If you are adding equations, it is important that you continue to use the ID logic that has been described ... \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "```markdown\n",
    "The audit label and crosslinking is tracked by #eq-an-nrc-2026. \n",
    "It is important to follow the custom label structure even for \n",
    "the invisible reference to make tracking easier. \n",
    "\n",
    "All equation text or variables and custom equation IDs should use the \\text function to ensure that formating is consistent throughout the Sci Doc. \n",
    "\n",
    "For extremely long equations, you may create manual breaks with the \\qquad function.\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {#eq-an-nrc-2026}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{CBW} = \\text{MW} \\times 0.06275\n",
    "$$\n",
    "<p style=\"text-align: right;\">[AN.NRC.2026]</p>\n",
    "\n",
    "All letters or acronyms included in equations should be wihtin the \\text{} function to ensure consistent formatting and avoid stray italices.\n",
    "Multiplication may be indicated with a \\times\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "Below is how the equation can be linked in other parts of the text: \n",
    "\n",
    "See [AN.NRC.2026](#eq-an-nrc-2026)<!-- @eq-an-nrc-2026 -->.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "This is how your equation and the linking should appear.\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {#eq-an-nrc-2026}\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{CBW} = \\text{MW} \\times 0.06275\n",
    "$$\n",
    "<p style=\"text-align: right;\">[AN.NRC.2026]</p>\n",
    "\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "See [AN.NRC.2026](#eq-an-nrc-2026)<!-- @eq-an-nrc-2026 -->.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Some equations may be too long to fit on a single line and within the margins. Unfortunately, you will need to manually break the equation into multiple lines. \n",
    "\n",
    "To do this, you can use the \\qquad function to create a break in the equation. Be sure to use the \\text function for all variables and text to ensure consistent formatting throughout the document.\n",
    "```markdown\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\\text{fecal\\_water} &= (1.987 \\times \\text{dry\\_matter\\_intake}) \\\\\n",
    "&\\quad + (0.348 \\times \\text{acid\\_detergent\\_fiber\\_concentrations}) \\\\\n",
    "&\\quad - (0.412 \\times \\text{crude\\_protein\\_concentration}) \\\\\n",
    "&\\quad - (0.074 \\times \\text{dry\\_matter\\_concentration}) \\\\\n",
    "&\\quad - (0.0057 \\times \\text{days\\_in\\_milk})\n",
    "$$\n",
    "\n",
    "<p style=\"text-align: right;\">[AN.EXC.18]</p>\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## Callouts, Recommendations, or Notes\n",
    "\n",
    "You may want to emphasize specific notes and annotations. Here is a helpful tool to do so correctly.\n",
    "\n",
    "```markdown\n",
    "::: {.callout-note}\n",
    "Callout text goes here\n",
    ":::\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "Your callout will appear the way it does below:\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.callout-note}\n",
    "Note: if only interested in a PDF version of the documentation (no website version), then the original LaTeX code\n",
    "can still be used and processed by quarto. For example, the bullet points works as the original LaTeX or translated\n",
    "into markdown syntax:\n",
    "\n",
    "```{{latex}}\n",
    "\\begin{itemize}\n",
    "    \\item first bullet point\n",
    "    \\item second bullet point\n",
    "    \\item ...\n",
    "\\end{itemize}\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "```{{markdown}}\n",
    "* first bullet point\n",
    "* second bullet point\n",
    "* ...\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "* first bullet point\n",
    "* second bullet point\n",
    "* ...\n",
    "\n",
    "but only the markdown works for all document types (html, pdf, word document, presentations, e-books, etc.).\n",
    ":::\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "## References\n",
    "\n",
    "Before adding a new reference to \"rufas.bib,\" check the file to ensure it has not already been added. All references should be listed alphabetically and then by year (most recent at the top). \n",
    "\n",
    "If you do need to add a bibliography, the correct structure is below. Pay special attention to the green text, this formatting is important to maintain consistentcy because it helps us with our auditing report and allows us to properly cite in-text.\n",
    "\n",
    "```bibtex\n",
    "Journal Articles\n",
    "@article{LASTNAME_YEAR,\n",
    "  author = {LASTNAME, FIRSTNAME},\n",
    "  title = {Title of the article in proper formatting},\n",
    "  journal = {Journal Title with proper NCBI Abbreviations},\n",
    "  year = {YEAR PUBLISHED},\n",
    "  volume = {VOLUME NUMBER},\n",
    "  pages = {PAGES}\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "Books \n",
    "\n",
    "@book{LASTNAME_YEAR,\n",
    "  author = {FIRSTNAME LASTNAME},\n",
    "  title = {Title of Book Referenced},\n",
    "  publisher = {Publisher},\n",
    "  year = {YEAR PUBLISHED},\n",
    "  isbn = {978-3-319-24277-4}\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "Online, Misc, Website (RARE USAGE)\n",
    "\n",
    "@online{quarto2024,\n",
    "  author = {Posit},\n",
    "  title = {Quarto Citations Guide},\n",
    "  year = {2024},\n",
    "  url = {https://quarto.org/docs/authoring/citations.html}\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "If there are 2 articles with the same author and same year, add the recommended \"a\" or \"b\" (e.g. ```bibtex @LASTNAME_YEARa vs @LASTNAME_YEARb```) as they are referenced.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "::: {.callout-note}\n",
    "## Previews and Audits\n",
    "\n",
